[2] Philippines (Negros Occidental)
Date: Mon 16 Jun 2008
Source: Sun Star [edited]
<http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/bac/2008/06/16/news/dengue.surges.in.3.cities.html>


Bago, Silay, and Talisay had the most number of dengue cases from
January-June [2008], a report submitted by Provincial Health officer
Luisa Efren to the Office of the Governor stated.

The report noted an uncommon rise in dengue cases in Bago City with
56 cases, Silay City with 55, and Talisay City with 52 recorded cases.

The 221 cases were collated from various hospitals in the cities and
municipalities of Negros Occidental, except Bacolod City.

Silay's dengue cases surged to 94 percent, considering it only had 3
cases for the same period last year [2007]. Talisay noted an 82
percent hike while Bago had a 46 percent increase.

Last year [2007], Victorias City topped the list of dengue-afflicted
areas with 56 cases. For the 1st 6 months of 2008, it recorded 21 or
a 60 percent reduction.

Bago noted 30 cases last year [2007] while Hinoba-an had 17,
including one fatality. This year [2008], Hinoba-an has 2 dengue cases.

Other areas with recorded dengue cases include La Carlota City (17),
Valladolid (5), Binalbagan (3), and Moises Padilla (1). [In 2007]
these areas had no dengue case.

The city of Sagay, meanwhile, recorded 26 cases this year [2008],
Manapla 20, San Carlos 16, Cadiz 16, Pontevedra 15, Hinigaran 14,
Kabankalan 14, Escalante 11, and EB Magalona 10 cases.

Except for Cadiz and Kabankalan, these areas noted a 50 percent hike
in the number of cases compared to last year [2007].

Himamaylan, on the other hand, has had 8 cases (from 2 last year
[2007]), Pulupandan 6 (3 cases last year), Calatrava 5 (2 cases last
year), Isabela 4 (2 cases last year), and La Castellana 4 (2 cases last year).

The Provincial Health Office has reiterated compliance to the "4S" in
dengue prevention: search and destroy mosquito-breeding places, safe
protection measures, seek early treatment, and saying no to
indiscriminate fogging.

[Byline: Gil Alfredo B. Severino]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur A-Lan Banks

[The "4S" campaign is a rational approach to control of _Aedes
aegypti_ mosquito control if the public can be educated to employ it.

An interactive map showing the location of Negros Occidental province
and the cities mentioned can be accessed at
<http://www.maplandia.com/philippines/region-6/negros-occidental/>. - Mod.TY]

