[3] Indonesia (Jakarta)
Date: Sat 14 Jun 2008
Source: Sinar Harapan [in Indonesian, machine trans., edited]
<http://www.sinarharapan.co.id/berita/0806/14/jab02.html>


Cases of dengue fever in the Jakarta Capital again increased over the
last 2 months. From April to May 2008, some 1000 additional cases
were reported.

The public relations official of the Health Service of Jakarta, Tini
Suryani, said on Friday afternoon (13 Jun 2008) that during April
there were at least 3741 cases and 3 of them died. In May, 4774 cases
were recorded with 4 deaths, indicating an increase of 1031 dengue
cases in Jakarta. For the month of June (up to 11 Jun [2008]) the
number of dengue cases in the Jakarta area reached 1164.

A member of the local government commission to control dengue, Achmad
Husein Alaydrus, questioned the eradication program of the
mosquito-breeding sites that has been carried out up until now. He
said the program must be reviewed again. It is not impossible that
implementation in the field has been inappropriate so that the dengue
case numbers in Jakarta have not declined.

Communities must be actively involved in eliminating
mosquito-breeding sites. The eradication of the mosquito-breeding
areas will not be successful if control activities are only carried
out every Friday, and not carried out together in the 5 Jakarta territories.

According to the Jakarta Regional Government, the eradication
programs of mosquito breeding-sites are carried out for 30 minutes
every Friday. This means that every Friday all office complexes must
allow 30 minutes in order to carry out the elimination of
mosquito-breeding sites in order to prevent dengue fever. This
pattern in fact was carried out in Cuba and was successful.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This level of community participation can be essential in reducing
dengue virus vector mosquito populations. The experience in Cuba
indicated that this control approach can be successful but difficult
to maintain. Cuba apparently did not maintain that level of community
effort and suffered a reemergence of _Aedes aegypti_ populations with
a resulting serious dengue epidemic in 2007. A community-based
cleanup campaign was reimplemented there.

An interactive map showing the location of Jarkarta on Java, can be accessed at
<http://encarta.msn.com/map_701513443/jakarta.html>. - Mod.TY]

